the Obama administration.

10:47.867 --> 10:52.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A firefight ensued, and the
commandos had to call in air
support from fighter aircraft

10:52.833 --> 10:54.967 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and helicopter gunships.

10:54.967 --> 10:59.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A Navy SEAL, Chief Petty Officer
Ryan Owens, was killed in the
battle and a transport aircraft

11:00.400 --> 11:02.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
suffered a hard landing
and had to be destroyed.

11:02.833 --> 11:07.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. military
acknowledged last night that
it had also likely killed
civilian noncombatants

11:08.833 --> 11:10.467 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
during the fight.

11:10.467 --> 11:13.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
White House spokesman
Sean Spicer spoke of
the mission today:

11:13.200 --> 11:16.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEAN SPICER, White House Press
Secretary: It's hard to ever
call something a complete

11:16.267 --> 11:20.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
success when you have a loss
of life or people injured.

11:20.233 --> 11:25.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think when you look at
the totality of what was gained
to prevent the future loss

11:25.067 --> 11:30.067 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of life here in America
and against our people
and our institutions
and probably throughout

11:32.133 --> 11:35.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the world in terms of what some
of these individuals could have
done, I think it is a successful

11:37.033 --> 11:39.133 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
operation by all standards.

11:39.133 --> 11:43.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: For more
on the raid and the strength
of the al-Qaida branch there,

11:43.000 --> 11:46.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm joined by David Sanger of
The New York Times and Richard
Atwood of the International

11:46.700 --> 11:51.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Crisis Group, which released
a report today on the strength
and capabilities of al-Qaida

11:51.533 --> 11:53.633 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Yemen.

11:53.633 --> 11:56.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
David, I want to ask you first,
most presidents say this is
the toughest decision that they

11:56.533 --> 12:01.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have, to send a member of the
armed forces into harm's way.

12:02.900 --> 12:05.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What was that decision-making
process like this time?

12:05.533 --> 12:10.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID SANGER, The New York
Times: Well, the process
was somewhat unusual, Hari.

12:10.200 --> 12:14.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Usually, a president goes
down in the Situation
Room, is presented with
what they call a full

12:14.967 --> 12:17.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
package for the attack.

12:17.000 --> 12:21.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's a legal assessment of
the legal authorities under
which they're doing these.

12:21.100 --> 12:25.167 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There's a risk assessment to the
commandos who would be doing it.

12:25.167 --> 12:30.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is a risk assessment
of what could happen to
civilians who are in the area.

12:33.100 --> 12:37.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
This particular attack
had been set up by the
Obama administration.

12:37.367 --> 12:42.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They had debated it, and
President Obama decided
about 10 days before
the end of his term that

12:44.333 --> 12:46.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he couldn't approve it because
the Pentagon really wanted
to go in under the complete

12:46.833 --> 12:49.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
cover of darkness,
a moonless night.

12:49.500 --> 12:54.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the next moonless night
wasn't going to be until after
he was no longer in office.

12:55.933 --> 12:59.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, they kicked this one over
to the new administration.

12:59.133 --> 13:04.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it looks like President
Trump got briefed on it, by and
large, at a dinner, not in the

13:05.300 --> 13:07.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Situation Room, not with
legal advisers around.

13:07.500 --> 13:10.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
His secretary of defense,
Jim Mattis, was there.

13:10.333 --> 13:12.867 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Vice President Pence was there.

13:12.867 --> 13:17.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Stephen Bannon, who has emerged
as the newest member of the
National Security Council, known

13:17.367 --> 13:22.367 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
really more for his political
advice than military, was there.

13:24.233 --> 13:27.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So was his new national
security adviser, Michael Flynn,
who is a veteran of many of

13:28.333 --> 13:29.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
these.

13:29.800 --> 13:33.267 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the discussion took
place in a dinner situation.

13:33.267 --> 13:37.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And he approved the
raid at that dinner.

13:37.100 --> 13:41.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I think one of the
questions, given how
many things have gone
wrong, is, would it

13:41.233 --> 13:46.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have been different if he had
been in the Situation Room
and perhaps had a different

13:48.633 --> 13:49.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
set of briefings?

13:49.900 --> 13:52.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The White House insists not.

13:52.100 --> 13:57.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's hard to call this much
of a success yet, because we
don't know what the value was of

13:59.133 --> 14:01.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the information they were
trying to exploit, which came
mostly from computers and cell

14:01.833 --> 14:03.900 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
phones.

14:03.900 --> 14:05.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And from everything we have
heard, they haven't had a
chance to assess that yet.

14:05.867 --> 14:09.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Richard
Atwood, put this in
perspective for us.

14:09.167 --> 14:11.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How strong is al-Qaida in Yemen?

14:11.233 --> 14:14.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD ATWOOD, International
Crisis Group: We -- as you said,
we published a report today

14:14.533 --> 14:17.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that looks at the evolution
of al-Qaida in Yemen.

14:17.200 --> 14:21.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, obviously, there's a lot
of talk about the Islamic State,
but, in Yemen, it's really

14:21.000 --> 14:24.967 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
al-Qaida that's done well
over the last few years.

14:24.967 --> 14:28.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Really, the civil war
-- it's been the main
beneficiary of the civil war.

14:28.700 --> 14:32.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And as fighting has escalated
between the two sides, between
President Hadi's government

14:32.967 --> 14:37.967 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and its Saudi-backed
international coalition
on the one hand against
the Houthis and former

14:39.900 --> 14:43.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
President Saleh, as fighting
has escalated, al-Qaida has
really been able to exploit the

14:43.100 --> 14:45.600 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
chaos.

14:45.600 --> 14:48.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's been able to control
territory and control
the town of Mukalla on
the Gulf of Aden for

14:48.333 --> 14:49.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
some time.

14:49.800 --> 14:51.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's strengthened its
ties to some communities.

14:51.933 --> 14:55.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It has very ties, close ties
with some of the other armed
groups that are fighting in

14:55.167 --> 14:57.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the anti-Houthi Saleh alliance.

14:57.900 --> 14:59.833 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
It's undoubtedly
got much richer.

14:59.833 --> 15:02.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's been able to
raid banks in Mukalla.

15:02.233 --> 15:04.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was embedded in the economy
in Mukalla for a long time.

15:04.900 --> 15:06.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it's much better armed.

15:06.900 --> 15:11.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's been able to gain guns and
weapons that have been passed
into other armed groups in

15:12.033 --> 15:14.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
which it's in an alliance.

15:14.200 --> 15:16.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So I think it's
stronger than ever.

15:16.533 --> 15:21.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, frankly, the longer the
war continues in Yemen, the
stronger al-Qaida is likely

15:22.000 --> 15:23.933 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to get.

15:23.933 --> 15:27.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I would just -- on the operation
yesterday, you know, I think
I agree with David that

15:27.833 --> 15:31.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it's very difficult to know
whether it's a success until
we know what information was

15:31.567 --> 15:33.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
retrieved.

15:33.700 --> 15:37.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On the other hand, I think
there's aspects of it that
are clearly not a success.

15:37.367 --> 15:39.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There's a lot of tribesmen
at the moment in Yemen.

15:39.400 --> 15:44.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And an operation like this
is more likely to radicalize
them, more likely to push them

15:46.233 --> 15:49.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into the arms of al-Qaida,
particularly then if it has a
high civilian cost, if it kills

15:51.267 --> 15:53.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
women, if it kills
children, particularly if
U.S. forces are involved.

15:53.467 --> 15:58.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It tends to feed
anti-Americanism and strengthen
those alliances between
the tribes in al-Qaida,

15:58.333 --> 16:00.467 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
which is what
al-Qaida profits from.

16:00.467 --> 16:03.767 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: David, did
any of thing from officials
or anybody else that you spoke

16:03.767 --> 16:08.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to say that that factored
into the Trump administration
or President Trump's
decision to do this?

16:10.733 --> 16:13.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID SANGER: We don't have a
lot of view into the decision
-- discussion that they

16:16.200 --> 16:19.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
had at the dinner table.

16:19.100 --> 16:22.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I think Richard raises one
of the most important points.

16:22.400 --> 16:27.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Over time, presidents learn
that the biggest risk out here
is not only the civilian risk

16:29.333 --> 16:33.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and the risk to American forces,
but whether - - as Donald
Rumsfeld used to say, whether

16:35.267 --> 16:39.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you're creating terrorists
faster than you're killing them.

16:39.833 --> 16:44.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And certainly, if you have
a case like this where there
appear to have been considerable

16:46.767 --> 16:50.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
civilian casualties, that may
well be the case, especially
because, even if some of

16:52.267 --> 16:55.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
those civilians may have taken
up arms and fired against
the SEALs, in the mythology

16:57.733 --> 17:00.667 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of what went on, you're
going to hear a story
of SEALs who dropped out
of the sky and suddenly

17:02.233 --> 17:05.267 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
attacked a remote
village in Yemen.

17:05.267 --> 17:09.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And you can imagine the
recruiting capability of that.

17:09.800 --> 17:14.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, you know, part of what's
going on here, Hari, is that you
have in the Trump administration

17:16.867 --> 17:20.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a group that believes that the
decision-making in these kind
of cases has to be shortened,

17:22.167 --> 17:26.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that more of the power has
to be devolved down to the
Pentagon, the commanders.

17:28.133 --> 17:31.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And yet, in the first case
that the president approved,
things went very badly wrong.

17:33.467 --> 17:37.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you have to wonder whether
or not that is going to have
the effect of making them

17:37.933 --> 17:42.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
think that they need to slow
down and think more about the
effects of these and get fuller

17:44.833 --> 17:46.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
briefings, or whether they're
simply going to say, look,
this happens sometimes.

17:46.800 --> 17:49.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All
right, David Sanger, Richard
Atwood, thank you both.

17:49.867 --> 17:52.367 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
RICHARD ATWOOD: Thank you.

17:52.367 --> 17:57.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID SANGER: Thank you.

17:59.367 --> 18:03.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, barely two
weeks into his term, President
Trump has shaken up global

18:06.500 --> 18:11.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
affairs through a series of
unilateral legal and diplomatic
moves and some blunt talk and

18:12.633 --> 18:14.700 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
tweets.

18:14.700 --> 18:19.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Longstanding American allies
and adversaries are asking
what the new administration has

18:20.867 --> 18:23.167 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in mind for its
relations abroad.

18:23.167 --> 18:28.167 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
One of several clues,
Iran's test-launch of a
medium-range ballistic
missile, which triggered

18:30.867 --> 18:35.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
